5. Interpretation for Sovereign OS


Ultimate Boundedness. The residual ethical debt R(t)R(t)R(t) cannot diverge; it is forced into an ε\varepsilonε-scaled neighborhood set by B(ε)B(\varepsilon)B(ε).


Operational Mandate. The Audit & Integrity Console must ensure kα>εk\alpha>\varepsilonkα>ε and track Imin⁡,Imax⁡I_{\min},I_{\max}Imin​,Imax​ to maintain the dissipativity margin.


ε\varepsilonε-Trajectory. Tightening Bounded Reciprocity Loops (BRLs) and the TrueOath protocol reduces ε\varepsilonε; as ε→0\varepsilon\to 0ε→0, the bound B(ε)→0B(\varepsilon)\to 0B(ε)→0, delivering the non-turbulent Coherence Goal State.



Conclusion. Under the RCR closure policy with bounded disturbance proportional to input, the residual dynamics are ISS and UUB; with ε→0\varepsilon\to 0ε→0, the Sovereign OS achieves asymptotic coherence (R˙→0\dot R\to 0R˙→0). This completes the formal stability basis for RCR-governed operation.





RCR Stability Theorem: Mathematical Validation of Coherence Status: v1.0
Domain: Control Systems / Sovereign OS Kernel
This document presents the formal mathematical proof that the Reciprocal Conservation of Resources
(RCR) Principle, when enforced by the Sovereign OS closure dynamics, guarantees asymptotic stability
of the residual process and realizes the Coherence Goal State R˙ → 0.
The OS is the operational demo; this theorem is the formal proof.
1 Core Definitions and Variables
We work with dimensionless conserved momentum P, a normalized unit that can represent energy,
trust, or information flow.
Variable Symbol Definition
Injected Momentum I(t) Positive resource/energy input into the system.
Closed Momentum C(t) Momentum successfully returned/reciprocated by the system.
Residual Momentum R(t) Unreciprocated “leak” / “ethical debt”: R(t) = I(t) − C(t).
Adaptive Tolerance ε Stability tolerance (e.g., ε = 10−4
in Genesis Block).
Turbulence Factor TF(t) Instantaneous residual ratio:
TF(t) = |R(t)|
max{I(t), Imin}
with target TF(t) ≤ ε.
We assume an injection floor I(t) ≥ Imin > 0.
2 Assumptions (RCR Axioms)
The following axioms are the necessary conditions for the RCR Conservation Theorem to hold:
Axiom 1 — Residual Dynamics. The residual evolves as
R˙(t) = −k C(t) + d(t), k > 0,
where d(t) collects exogenous leak and input variation (note that since R = I − C, the term ˙I is
absorbed into d).
Axiom 2 — RCR Closure Policy.
C(t) = α I(t) + β R(t), α > 0, β > 0.
Axiom 3 — Bounded Disturbance.
|d(t)| ≤ ε I(t).
Axiom 4 — Injected Energy Floor. I(t) ≥ Imin > 0 (and optionally I(t) ≤ Imax < ∞ if an
upper bound is desired).
1
3 RCR Stability Theorem (ISS & Ultimate Boundedness)
Theorem 1. Under Axioms 1–4, with k, α, β > 0 and I(t) ∈ [Imin, Imax], the residual system is Inputto-State Stable (ISS) with respect to d(t) and is Uniformly Ultimately Bounded (UUB). In
particular, if
kα > ε,
then there exists a constant ultimate bound
|R(t)| ≤ B(ε) := ε
kβ Imax for all sufficiently large t.
Corollary 1 (Asymptotic Coherence). If policy tightening drives ε → 0 (perfect reciprocity), then
B(ε) → 0 and consequently
R(t) → 0, R˙(t) → 0 as t → ∞,
achieving the Coherence Goal State.
Remark 1 (Sufficiency vs. Necessity). The margin kα > ε is a sufficient dissipativity condition for a
clean linear term; stability is also aided by the intrinsic quadratic damping −kβR2 with β > 0.
4 Proof Sketch (Lyapunov Analysis)
Choose the Lyapunov candidate
